@startuml llm-module-detail
title "LLM Module - Natural Language Processing & Response Rendering"

!define ACCENTCOLOR #4A90E2
!define TRAITCOLOR #E8F4F8
!define CLIENTCOLOR #F0E6FF

skinparam style strictuml
skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam NoteBackgroundColor #FFFACD
skinparam NoteBorderColor #FFD700
skinparam ClassBackgroundColor #F5F5F5
skinparam ClassBorderColor ACCENTCOLOR

' LLM Client Trait and Implementations
package "LLM Client Abstraction" {
    interface LLMClientTrait #TRAITCOLOR <<trait>> {
        + query(text: &str): Result<String>
        + query_with_context(text: &str, context: Option<String>): Result<String>
        + query_with_history(text: &str, history: &[String]): Result<String>
    }

    class HttpLLMClient implements LLMClientTrait #CLIENTCOLOR {
        - base_url: String
        - client: reqwest::Client
        --
        + new(base_url: String): Self
        + with_timeout(timeout: Duration): Self
        + query(text: &str): Result<String>
        - send_request(request: LLMRequest): Result<LLMResponse>
        --
        **HTTP-based LLM client**
        **Tech**: reqwest for async HTTP
        **Timeout**: 30 seconds default
        **Status**: Ready for real endpoint (endpoint TBD)
    }

    class MockLLMClient implements LLMClientTrait #CLIENTCOLOR {
        - response_cache: HashMap<String, String>
        --
        + new(): Self
        + with_response(query: String, response: String): Self
        + query(text: &str): Result<String>
        --
        **Mock client for testing**
        **Use**: Development and unit tests
        **Responses**: Deterministic, configurable
    }

    note right of LLMClientTrait
        **LLM Client Interface**:
        - query(): Basic text query
        - query_with_context(): With additional context
        - query_with_history(): With command history (M2/M3)

        **Dependency Injection**:
        Different clients can be swapped at runtime
        Production ↔ Testing without code changes
    end note

    note bottom of HttpLLMClient
        **HTTP Client Details**:
        - Async/await with tokio
        - 30 second timeout (configurable)
        - Retries NOT implemented (M2 feature)
        - Error handling: Network timeouts, bad responses
        - Auth: Placeholder for future implementation
    end note

    note bottom of MockLLMClient
        **Mock Client Usage**:
        ```rust
        let mock = Arc::new(MockLLMClient::new()
            .with_response(
                "list files".to_string(),
                "Use: ls -la".to_string()
            )
        );
        ```
        Perfect for testing without real API calls
    end note
}

' LLM Request/Response Data Structures
package "LLM Data Models" {
    class LLMRequest {
        + query: String
        + context: Option<String>
        --
        Serialized to JSON for HTTP request
    }

    class LLMResponse {
        + text: String
        + metadata: Option<serde_json::Value>
        --
        Deserialized from HTTP response JSON
    }

    note right of LLMRequest
        **Request Serialization**:
        ```json
        {
          "query": "how do I list files?",
          "context": null
        }
        ```
        Uses serde for JSON serialization
    end note

    note right of LLMResponse
        **Response Deserialization**:
        ```json
        {
          "text": "Use the ls command: ls -la",
          "metadata": {
            "model": "gpt-3.5",
            "tokens": 42
          }
        }
        ```
    end note
}

' Response Rendering
package "Response Rendering & Formatting" {
    class ResponseRenderer {
        + render_markdown(response: &str): Vec<String>
        + highlight_code(code: &str, language: &str): String
        --
        **Responsibilities**:
        - Parse markdown from LLM response
        - Format for TUI display
        - Apply syntax highlighting
    }

    note right of ResponseRenderer
        **Markdown Support** (M1 Basic Only):
        Implemented:
        - Code blocks with syntax highlighting
          ```rust
          fn hello() { println!("world"); }
          ```
        - Inline code formatting
        - Basic text formatting (bold, italic)
        - Lists (bullet points)
        - Headers (# ## ###)

        Not yet implemented (M2/M3):
        - Tables
        - Images
        - Embedded links
        - Complex nested structures
        - LaTeX/Math rendering
    end note

    class SyntaxHighlighter {
        - supported_languages: [rust, python, bash, json, javascript, etc.]
        --
        + highlight_rust(code: &str): Vec<AnsiString>
        + highlight_python(code: &str): Vec<AnsiString>
        + highlight_bash(code: &str): Vec<AnsiString>
        + highlight_json(code: &str): Vec<AnsiString>
        + highlight_javascript(code: &str): Vec<AnsiString>
    }

    note right of SyntaxHighlighter
        **Syntax Highlighting**:
        Technology: syntect (Sublime syntax definitions)
        Colors: ANSI escape codes for TUI

        Supported Languages:
        - Rust (primary for DevOps context)
        - Python (scripting)
        - Bash/Shell (scripting)
        - JSON (configuration, API)
        - JavaScript/TypeScript (infrastructure)
        - YAML (configuration)
        - Go (microservices)
        - C/C++ (systems)

        Output: ANSI escape codes for terminal display
    end note

    note bottom of ResponseRenderer
        **Rendering Pipeline**:
        1. LLM returns markdown text
        2. Parse markdown structure
        3. For each code block:
           a. Detect language (from ``` marker)
           b. Apply syntax highlighting
           c. Convert to ANSI codes
        4. Format text sections
        5. Convert to Vec<String> for TUI display
        6. Add to OutputBuffer
    end note
}

' Message Formatting Integration
package "Message Formatting" {
    class MessageFormatter {
        + command(input: &str): String
        + error(message: &str): String
        + success(message: &str): String
        + info(message: &str): String
        + warning(message: &str): String
        --
        Formats messages with ANSI colors
    }

    note right of MessageFormatter
        **ANSI Color Codes**:
        - Green for successful commands
        - Red for errors
        - Blue for info messages
        - Yellow for warnings
        - Cyan for prompts
        - Magenta for status messages

        Used for:
        - Labeling command output
        - Error messages
        - Status updates
        - User prompts
    end note
}

' Integration with Orchestrators
package "Orchestrator Integration" {
    class NaturalLanguageOrchestrator {
        - llm_client: Arc<dyn LLMClientTrait>
        - renderer: ResponseRenderer
        --
        + handle_query(query: &str, state, ui): Result<()>
    }

    note right of NaturalLanguageOrchestrator
        **Integration Workflow**:
        1. Receive natural language query
        2. Send to LLM via llm_client.query()
        3. On success:
           a. Get response text from LLM
           b. Render markdown via ResponseRenderer
           c. Add formatted lines to OutputBuffer
           d. Update TerminalState
           e. Re-render TUI
        4. On error:
           a. Format error message
           b. Display to user
           c. Suggest alternatives
    end note
}

' Relationships
ResponseRenderer --> SyntaxHighlighter
HttpLLMClient --> LLMRequest
HttpLLMClient --> LLMResponse
MockLLMClient --> LLMRequest
MockLLMClient --> LLMResponse
NaturalLanguageOrchestrator --> LLMClientTrait
NaturalLanguageOrchestrator --> ResponseRenderer
NaturalLanguageOrchestrator --> MessageFormatter

